solution.p:
View this system as \linearsystem{C}{\vect{b}}, where C is the 4\times 4 matrix from  and \vect{b}=\colvector{-4\\4\\-20\\9}.  Since C was seen to be nonsingular in   says the  solution, which is unique by , is given by\inverse{C}\vect{b}=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                38 & 18 & -5 & -2\\
                96 & 47 & -12 & -5\\
                -39 & -19 & 5 & 2\\
                -16 & -8 & 2 & 1
                \end{bmatrix}
                \colvector{-4\\4\\-20\\9}
                =
                \colvector{2\\-1\\-2\\1}.  Notice that this solution can be easily checked in the original system of equations.

The coefficient matrix of this system of equations isA=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                 1 & 2 & -1 \\
                 2 & 5 & -1 \\
                 -1 & -4 & 0
                \end{bmatrix}and the vector of constants is \vect{b}=\colvector{-3\\-4\\2}.  So by  we can convert the system to the form A\vect{x}=\vect{b}.   Row-reducing this matrix yields the identity matrix so by  we know A is nonsingular.  This allows us to apply  to find the unique solution as\vect{x}
                =
                \inverse{A}\vect{b}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}
                 -4 & 4 & 3 \\
                 1 & -1 & -1 \\
                 -3 & 2 & 1
                \end{bmatrix}
                \colvector{-3\\-4\\2}
                =
                \colvector{2\\-1\\3}.  Remember, you can check this solution easily by evaluating the matrix-vector product  A\vect{x} ().

We can reformulate the linear system as a vector equality with a matrix-vector product via .  The system is then represented by A\vect{x}=\vect{b} where
                    A&=
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    1 & -1 & 2 \\
                    1 & 0 & -2\\
                    2 & -1 & -1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &
                    \vect{b}
                    &=\colvector{5\\-8\\-6}
                .  According to , if A is nonsingular then the (unique) solution will be given by \inverse{A}\vect{b}.  We attempt the computation of \inverse{A} through , or with our favorite computational device and obtain,
                    \inverse{A}=
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                     2 & 3 & -2 \\
                     3 & 5 & -4 \\
                     1 & 1 & -1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                So by , we know A is nonsingular, and so the unique solution is
                    \inverse{A}\vect{b}
                    =
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                     2 & 3 & -2 \\
                     3 & 5 & -4 \\
                     1 & 1 & -1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    \colvector{5\\-8\\-6}
                    =
                    \colvector{-2\\-1\\3}
                .
